TY  - JOUR
AU  - Duggan, Mark G.
T1  - Hospital Ownership and Public Medical Spending*
PY  - 2000
Y1  - 2000/11/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355300555097
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 115
IS  - 4
SP  - 1343
EP  - 1373
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - The hospital market is served by firms that are private for-profit, private not-for-profit, and government-owned and operated. I use a plausibly exogenous change in hospital financing that was intended to improve medical care for the poor to test three theories of organizational behavior. I find that the critical difference between the three types of hospitals is caused by the soft budget constraint of government-owned institutions. The decision-makers in private not-for-profit hospitals are just as responsive to financial incentives and are no more altruistic than their counterparts in profit-maximizing facilities. My final set of results suggests that the significant increase in public medical spending examined in this paper has not improved health outcomes for the indigent.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355300555097
ER  - 



